`,c.jsxs(t.p,{children:["In the previous chapter, acceleration was set directly — the ball pointed toward the mouse and accelerated at a fixed rate. That worked, but it sidestepped a question that sits at the heart of physics simulation: ",c.jsx(t.em,{children:"where does acceleration come from?"})," The answer is forces."]}),`
`,c.jsxs(t.p,{children:["A ",c.jsx(t.strong,{children:"force"})," is a vector that causes an object to accelerate. That's it. Wind pushes. Gravity pulls. Friction resists. Each of these is a force — a vector quantity with a direction and a magnitude — and each one produces acceleration. The bridge between the two is Newton's second law, which we'll get to shortly."]}),`
`,c.jsx(t.h2,{id:"newton-laws-of-motion",children:"Newton Laws of Motion"}),`
`,c.jsx(t.p,{children:"Isaac Newton's laws of motion, published in 1687, remain the foundation of classical mechanics. For simulation purposes, all three are directly relevant."}),`
`,c.jsxs(t.p,{children:[c.jsx(t.strong,{children:"The first law"})," states that an object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion at the same velocity, unless acted upon by a net external force. In code, this is already the default behavior: if you apply no acceleration, ",c.jsx(t.code,{children:"velocity"})," never changes and the object drifts forever in a straight line. No special handling required — inertia is free."]}),`
`,c.jsxs(t.p,{children:[c.jsx(t.strong,{children:"The second law"})," is the most important for simulation. It states:"]}),`
